Here's the full migration. Your code has **four** Thread.Abort-related patterns:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| Cancellable work loop | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` |
| `Thread.Abort()` call | `Stop()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | `ProcessLoop` | `OperationCanceledException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop` | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. Loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation — replaces Thread.Abort

        // Wait with a bounded timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key pitfalls to watch for

1. **`GetNextItem` must accept and respect the token.** If it blocks on a `BlockingCollection`, use `collection.Take(token)`. If it blocks on a `WaitHandle`, use `WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { handle, token.WaitHandle })`. If it calls `Thread.Sleep`, replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. **If you don't thread the token through, cancellation will stall at the blocking call.**

2. **`ProcessItem` needs checkpoints too.** If it does long-running work, call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular intervals inside it, otherwise cancellation waits until the current item finishes entirely.

3. **`CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`.** The class now implements `IDisposable` to avoid leaking the CTS's internal timer and callbacks.

4. **Cancellation is not immediate.** Unlike `Thread.Abort` which injected an exception anywhere, cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Design your checkpoint frequency based on acceptable shutdown latency.

5. **The `when` filter on the catch matters.** `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated `OperationCanceledException` from some other source.

6. **`Join` replaces `Sleep` + `Abort`.** The original code did `Sleep(2000)` then `Abort()`. Now `Cancel()` signals immediately and `Join(2s)` waits for the thread to finish cooperatively — no force-kill needed.
